column169: On December 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallond drum of printing ink was damaged and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Coastal Environmental Solutions (CES) to remediate the impacted site. CES personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the ink-impacted trailer floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon overpack and all impacted waste and absorbents collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon pail.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately two (2) gallons of material released from one (1) 55-gallon metal drum due to the drum being punctured by a nail when a skid was broken at the terminal. The release material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and containerized it and the PM solvent into one (1) 10-gallon poly drum. Addition PM solvent was containerized in one (1) 65-gallon medal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

Pkg missing required markings for shipment containing hazardous contents. 1 x 24 oz. bottle of Hand Sanitizer 70% has a Flash point of 25-27 C (77-80.6 F) and typically ships as "Ltd Qty".  Loose and missing trigger spray heads of non-hazardous liquid contents allowed liquid to leak wetting and damaging the contents and carton. Excessive weight of the contents and weakening from the leaked liquid caused the corner of the carton to rip and glue to fail on the closure tape.

On December 3, 2024, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN1760 were crushed in transit and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior and surrounding freight. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. The crew utilized neutralizers, absorbents, and hand tools to remove any product. All waste and the damaged pails were containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.
attachment Name:PIC1.png

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 15-gallon drum containing hazardous product, Nalco Stabrex#ST70. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5-gallon release onto the wooden trailer floor in a 2'x2' area as a result of improper loading/inadequate preparation for transportation. The contractor used sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the release and applied oil dry to clean-up the spill. The damaged drum was overpacked into one 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. The neutralized and impacted oil dry was containerized into a separate 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste generated from the spill response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

XPO Logistics terminal XSJ experienced a UN1760 2204 Descaler-Acid Pickle release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-teaspoon of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the poly tote lid due to a crack in the top of the tote. The material was gravity fed from the damaged tote into a new one for shipment on. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with absorbents and PPE into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage
attachment Name:pixxx6.png

XPO Logistics terminal LTU experienced a UN1814 Mar-Tek 911 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the poly tote lid due to a cracked tote. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with impacted pads from cleanup into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage

XPO Logistics terminal XNW experienced a UN2920 Dicoco Dimethyl Ammonium Chloride release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4 ounces of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the poly tote lid due to a loose cap. The cap was tightened and re-secured onto the tote. The tote was then decontaminated, wiped down, and secured for continued shipment on. The impacted pads used to clean the tote were containerized into a 5-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
